<title>USA: Greenspan opposes big government stake in stocks.</title>
<headline>Greenspan opposes big government stake in stocks.</headline>
<dateline>WASHINGTON 1997-01-30</dateline>
<text>
<p>Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan said that he opposed the idea of the United States goverment becoming a huge stakeholder in common stocks through the Social Security System.</p>
<p>In testimony before the Senate Finance Committee, Greenspan said he did not believe that it would be possible to insulate business decisions from government meddling in such an arrangement.</p>
<p>&quot;It would make me very uncomforable,&quot; he said, adding: &quot;under no condition would I envisage as desirable to have any significant equity holdings, claims on ownership of American business, in the hands of the Federal Government.&quot;</p>
</text>
